content: Please add te edit mood description feature to fix typos.
Great, quick, educational and action oriented
I love its gives me more words to describe how I feel and makes you really think about whats really making you feel this way
Not a very complex app, but I have found it to be helpful.
I like this app quite a bit. I wish there were some more nuanced choices, and more emotion options. Best used when paired with the book!

Too laborious to use. If you want to identify your emotions in the moment, too bad - there is an extended delay when you open the app, and it takes several clicks to get to the emotion identification part. There's then a series of questions you can't skip, before the emotion is saved. Not the app I was looking for - too slow and frustrating.
Has really helped teach me how to identify my emotions better and develop a broader vocabulary for how I'm feeling

Read the book , love the app ! "Permission to Feel" is inspiring and helps me professionally as a Manager , coach and at home as a parent, and personally for my own emotion mgmt. I just started to use the app, and already I am learning to better recognize my emotion. It also provides the space to contemplate and the pause that allows me to choose differently, or stay willingly with that emotion. Book + App if you are nterested understanding in your emotional health and those of others.
Please resolve the issue.iam getting black screen.

Great app. But unfortunately for me my phone has identified regular app crashes . It doesn't seem to affect the performance of the app, but I'm hoping it isn't draining my battery unnecessarily. Hopefully this is fixed in a future update

Was suggested to me by a friend. I have no idea if it works because after selecting my color and asking for a reflection, I cannot go any further. My only obvious choice is to cancel. This is on a moto x4, it's not a new phone, but it is running Android 9.

Nice clean app that is easy to use. Its been great learning the words for different emotions. The app leads you to really think about how you're feeling and also identify the word for the feeling. Its fun to track my emotions and what I was doing at the time of certain emotions.
Easy to use and helpful

I really like the concept of this app but there are a few features I wish it had. I wish I could run reports to see calendars/timelines/bar graphs/ticker charts that show mood trends on a day, week, month, and year scale and be able to see patterns like time of day, activity, and season and that would also reflect trends over time of improvement or regression in overall mood. I also wish I could set reminder times with push notifications that would remind me to record my mood at certain times.

Great idea. Could be better. Next button is completely missing for some feelings on the comment screen. On the others it only shows as a grey square. If "next" is on the button, it's too far down to aopear on my screen. Love the data, colors, etc.

Found this looking for apps that "could help coping with autism" to put it simply. It's not revolutionary but it has helped me, an autistic adult (which I'm ashamed to say), a lot dealing with my emotions. Overall, I'm satisfied and it's worth the price.

So far, I think this is an awesome App. Better for me than simple journaling. My one wish is that it had a native reminder/notification option. I'd like to, say, twice a day, have this app remind me to check in on how I feel.
A nice tool to help develop your emotional vocabulary. Although limited to 100 words, it's a good way to start growing in this area. I wish I would have had access to this growing up.

To the developer: (originally a 5 üòì). This app has been really helpful in assisting me to identify emotions and use corrective measures where appropriate. But I have a problem with the update in that I can no longer add my own suggestions, which was key to forming specific, personalized habits/attitudes. Will this be possible again or is there another way to do this in the new version that I'm not aware of? Thank you.

Great for defining how I'm feeling at any moment
It really helps me to monitor my emotions and their cause, thereby allowing me to recognize patterns and strengths/areas to improve.
A fantastic way to explore the subtle differences between emotional and mood states. Worth paying for.

Edit: I have been using the app for a week or two, and suddenly all of my information is missing and I'm being asked to sign up and login. Others have reported the same issue & no response from the admin. It's fraudulent if you don't address these complaints. You're collecting money for a product that doesn't do what its intended. Fix needed urgently. Boo!
Very helpful in my journey of learning about my own emotional intelligence.
Recommended by my therapist. It has helped to monitor mood swings and gives space for me to look at patterns and causations.

I like this. I'm reading Permission to Feel and I'm finding it very enlightening. My biggest frustration with the app is the definitions of the emotions are limited. Anxious and nervous are far too similar... And understanding the differences in emotions is at the crux of this. Definitely improvements to be made and I'm excited to see them implemented in the future!

It's a great way to pay attention + learn about your moods + what might be causing them. Definitely helps to get clear + helps to see patterns in one's day or week if needing some awareness into areas of unhappiness or stress, etc. This was recommended to me by my therapist to track my moods. It helps + easy to use!

The way the emotions are laid out is extremely helpful for me me. I feel the energy/intensity of emotions much more than any other aspect of the emotions so it does help to narrow it down. The definitions of each emotion help me to understand when I am may be labeling something more intensely than necessary and giving me the oppurtunity to choose less intense lnguage actually de-esculates me. The suggestions for shifting mood are normal things, but things I forget exist, so it is helpful for me.

Learned more nuanced emotion words. This lets me continue to (try to) practice the RULER concept every day. I too really would like to see the world peace where everyone is compassionate and empathetic towards one another. Thank you, from the bottom of my heart, for what you have done and continue to do, professor Marc Brackett! Brilliant!

Great for mindfulness! I heard about this app through my teacher certification program and it's not only great for helping me to process my own feelings but can be an excellent tool for the classroom in helping kids to understand their feelings and work through them appropriately. Also my partner is reading Mark Brackett's (the creator of this app) book and is really enjoying it.
I need help with emotional intelligence and finding help in this app

Not great initially. I have to untether my keyboard every time I log a feeling because the 'next' button is underneath it. Second, when I indicate that I want to shift my mood, the responses so far have been less than helpful. I probably won't use that option much, but will focus on learning the vocabulary. Finally, more about the instrument than the app, many words which are found in Bracket's book "Permission to Feel", such as guilty, embarrassed, humiliated, are not in the grid.
Needs to be abke to track more than one emotion at a time.
Good for helping me pause and identify a feeling, then reflect on why. Very useful and it's helping me to create a great new habit.

The colours and moods are great. I really like this app although it would be a 5 star if i could write more in my notes. I barley get a couple of sentences to describe why I am feeling how I feel. I hope this changes.

Great app and idea. Concur with other reviewers about being able to view the sentence describing the mood!

It's a great app. I just wish we had options to record mood at another time. Or to record the mood and be able to edit the feeling itself or the *time* of it. When I'm having such great time, I can't pull up the app to record it!

For myself, someone trying to understand how they feel with the aid of your app I found myself discouraged and frustrated because all I got was nice-sounding vocabulary words that I had to look up in the dictionary to define; whose definition required defining other words I did not understand leading to a big circle of nothingness that left me feeling worse than I started. To make things worse, the suggestions given to improve my mood are all cliche. Thanks for nothing.

If there were further developments in the app I would like if it was possible to easily pick multiple emotions at one time instead of needing to start the process over again. I would also appreciate if the app kept track of the sentences I wrote associated with each emotion. Now I'm using two apps to keep track of these.

Edit: Its strange that thrilled is below excited on the energy scale. I think they've been accisently swapped. Good emotion tracking app, definetly gives you a larger spectrum to choose from than other apps I've tried. I wish the shift feature was more sophisticated, maybe have it link to helpful articles and more options to where we want to shift. It automatically assumes I should shift to joy which isn't always the case.

This is a really cool emotional tracker! I love being able to explore the different emotions and picking the best one that fits. But it would be really helpful if they defined the terms too. My biggest issue though is that I can't view any of the articles or videos in the learning area. :(

This is a great app. I have complex trauma/CPTSD and Keeping track of my emotions is so challenging! This is a really great teaching tool and has inadvertently helped me with my self worth! Naming emotions is super helpful and helps to separate me from my problems and experiences.
I like how it provides specific emotions so that I can be more precise in what I am feeling. I like the suggestions provided for when I want to or need to change my mood. I love the cumulative stats!

I find myself struggling at times to find the ones that are a match, and would appreciate greater variety of choices. If possible, create the ability to identify more than one emotion at a time. Rare to be feeling just one thing. I suppose you could just go back and do multiple times... Expand strategies for shifting mood; this is the weakest part of the app. From my experience, the strategies tend to not be very practical, are pretty repetitive and limited.

Really helpful and insightful app, helps me to investigate my feeling and moods and focus on how I want to feel. Would be nice to see a yearly over view as well as monthly. Also if you share it with a friend does it just say how your feeling or the comments as well? I'd prefer it to just say how I'm feeling but not why as this can be very private.

Helpful App

Fantastic way to help navigate emotions! Thank you

This app is the best mood monitoring app I've encountered. I've tried out and used different ones for years (2012 onward) and have found none as comprehensive on emotional and mood types as this. It's intuitive to use, and educational. I learn more about emotions states every time I open this app. The only thing it's missing is notifications or reminders. If it could be set to notify me daily (or better yet, 3-5 times daily at times I specify), I would use it more and get more out of it.

I also heard about the app from the book Permission to Feel. It's got a nice UI and is easy to use. I do wish it offered push notification reminders throughout the day to check-in. It would also make sense to be able to tag multiple emotions at once, like another reviewer mentioned, to provide a more nuanced expression of what you're feeling, which is often a few different things simultaneously. The app Pacifica is what I was used to using for check-ins, and it lets you select many at a time.

My main complaint is the limited options of feeling to choose from. There are 25 words in each quadrant, summing up to only 100 words for feelings. This is intended to teach emotional literacy. It should allow more nuance. Perhaps adding the option for more words? Some of the feeling placement is odd too. (Focused = high energy?)

*NB: edit at end*  Seems pretty damn good. Only a two main points of hesitation:   1) have to select a mood and then hit the (i) icon to have it defined for you----a simple hold action on a mood that pops up a definition would be a *big* help for those of us who have trouble articulating how we feel;   2) when I want to SHIFT to green it seems to have yellowish quotes & strategies (all about movement & energy) and when I want to SHIFT to yellow it instead has greenish quotes & strategies (all about peace & stillness).   Would definitely change to a 5 star with improvements to these area---particularly the second thing, as it's kinda a major stumbling block when I'm being given help to SHIFT to a mood I don't want to go to... ;)  {EDIT} Also, for heaven's sake, please let us *edit* and/or *delete* entries. The idea, concept, and unique function of this app give it immense potential. Sadly, there are numerous programming glitches and/or device compatibility issues, along with grammatical/spelling errors within the app. These problems are holding it back from becoming the highly rated special purpose tool it could be.  The first major issue presents itself when attempting to register a date of birth. The app forces the data to be entered through the device calendar, making the process inefficient and frustrating.  After selecting an entry, certain dates will then display incorrectly, some even cause the app to crash without storing the DOB data.  A spelling error presents itself upon selecting the help option within the settings menu. The help page describes the purpose of the app, and, in the second bullet point, the word vocabulary is misspelled.  Although this is not a major issue in the app's functionality, it does not look very professional.  "Vocatulary" is not an official word in the English language, as far as I know.  There are also a couple of key options missing within the settings for the app.  Typically, an app giving a user the ability to create new tasks will then also include the ability to remove those same user-created tasks. The ability to delete old reminders that may no longer be needed and/or wanted in the reminders list would be nice for organizational purposes and to maintain optimal task processing.  As I initially stated, I really like the concept and purpose of this app, but these issues really need to be addressed in order to create a professional appearance, in turn, boosting ratings and increasing the appeal/popularity of this unique app.

The concept of this app is simple and powerful. I used it without fail on the iPhone for more than a year. This Android implement ration, however, is terrible and tremendously frustrating.   In less than a week of using the app, I've lost my data 3 times. This seems mostly related to the terrible authentication implementation, which is neither necessary nor valuable in anyway.   I have not once logged in successfully-I can't imagine that this was tested even once. By clicking Get Started I can enter the app and record moods, however, that fails randomly and unexpectedly.  This app is not worth your time as a free app, let alone a paid app.

I'm a bit disappointed. I assumed this would be a great app for my class room... instead it is just a personal mood tracker. I would highly suggest for the ability to click a "dot" and it automatically be saved (multiple classroom accounts). This would make it easy for students to simply click the phone on the way into my door as my greeting and I would have instant data that I can show on my doc cam or to other students without the hassle of sticky notes or magnets. If you plan updating the app to allow this i'll keep it on my phone. Otherwise I would like a refund if possible.
